the Context of World Literature -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first volume to consistently examine Soviet engagement with world literature from multiple institutional and disciplinary perspectives: intellectual history, literary history and theory, comparative literature, translation studies, diaspora studies. Its emphasis is on the lessons one could learn from the Soviet attention to world literature; as such, the present volume makes a significant contribution to current debates on world literature beyond the field of Slavic and East European Studies and foregrounds the need to think of world literature pluralistically, in a manner that is not restricted by the agendas of Anglophone academe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aSoviet literaturexForeign influences. 0aSoviet literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh  aSlavic literature.  aSoviet Union.  aSoviet internationalism.  aUSSR.  acomparative literature.  adiaspora studies.  ahistory of the left.  aintellectual history.  aliterary exiles.  aliterary history.  aliterary theory.  atranslation studies.  atransnationalism.  aworld literature.1 aBelskaia, Evgeniia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Katerina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDjagalov, Rossen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDjagalov, Rossen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrank, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhotimsky, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorotkov, Georgii, econtri